snippet.textDisplay:
For people still debating over the language, here's what I have to say:

Odia = Kosali (as spoken in Western Odisha; Sambalpuri, Kalahandiya, etc.) + Utkaliya Odia (Sanskritized Odia as spoken in northern Odisha)+ Desiya Odia (as spoken in southern Odisha; e.g: Ganjami) + All the other minor variations spread over the entire diverse topography

Feeling proud and happy! :)
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay:
Yes, it is a proud moment for all Odisha dwellers all over the world to have recognized the song and coke studio to be producing a remix, but should not they have the least bit courtesy to inform the original song writer or the singers regarding the production. Leave apart the singing, the presence of the singers themselves on the stage would have spread fire all around.  But the singers, the lyricist and the song composer are all unaware of this until they were told about it.

The least they could do is have the original singers sing it being the studio that promotes folk singing.

Miss Krishna patel and Dr. jitendra harpal are astounded of having not known about it.

I am eagerly waiting for this song. And very much concerned seeing a lot of comments saying "its not an Odia song, its a Sambalpuri song". I am originally from Sambalpur part and I am a proud  ODIA. 

And for those oxymoron people, not leaving a single oppurtunity to make a war, I must say Sambalpuri is a dialect, not a language, that too dialect of ODIA, which is now among the 6 CLASSICAL LANGUAGES OF INDIA(even hindi is not there in that list). So grow up people. See what your language is.
